1 Herring Updates

1.1 Do we see changes in population size consistent with collapse and lack of recovery in Prince William Sound?

These are results that I showed last time. Effective population size Ne estimated using nucleotide diversity and mutation rate (2.0e-9).

But this is a long-term estimate of Ne. We can also estimate short term Ne using temporal sampling.

Suppose we have an isolated random mating population with discrete generations and we wish to measure its (average) Ne during a certain period of time. We take two samples from the population, the first sample at the beginning (generation 0) and the second sample at the end (generation t) of the period of time. The two samples are genotyped to estimate allele frequencies. Then Ne = t / F where F is standardized variance in the temporal changes of allele frequency.

Below, we can see variance in allele frequency change for Prince William Sound, Sitka Sound, and Togiak Bay populations.

Higher variance in allele frequency changes corresponds to lower estimate of Ne.

Does this line up with our expectations?

1.2 Loss of function mutations

Given that PWS experienced a population bottleneck, we might expect that deleterious alleles rose to higher frequencies in PWS relative to healthy populations due to genetic drift.

Step 1. Measure per-site Fst (as opposed to windowed Fst) to look at divergence between (PWS vs. healthy populations) at individual sites.

Step 2. Use the awesome Variant Effect Predictor tool from Ensembl to identify deleterious alleles (particularly loss-of-function alleles)

1.2.4 Variant Effect Predictor VEP

Ensemble resource. Input is:

chromosome position Ref_Allele Alt_Allele

VEP outputs the effect of SNP in coding region.
Annotations relevant to LoF:
stop_gained
start_lost
stop_lost
missense
